This is expected and reflects architectural differences in rule interpretation:

| Aspect | axe-core | @siteimprove/alfa |
|--------|----------|-------------------|
| Rule granularity | Aggregates multiple checks per SC (e.g., 1.4.1 includes *all* color-only cues) | One W3C ACT Rule per `Result`; 1.4.1 splits into multiple ACT rules (e.g., `color-contrast`, `non-text-contrast`) |
| Outcome semantics | `violations[]` includes *all* failures, even edge cases | `Audit.run()` returns only *verified* ACT rule outcomes (`Passed`/`Failed`/`Inapplicable`/`CanNotTell`) |
| False positives | May flag low-contrast *patterns* without full context (e.g., hover states) | Requires explicit context (e.g., interactive state, CSS cascade) to `Failed` |
| Manual review | Often requires triage of `axe.run()` output | `CanNotTell` outcomes should be queued for human review |

For SC 1.4.1 specifically:
- axe may count *every* element using color *alone* (e.g., red links, green success icons without icons)
- Alfa may only flag cases where *all* following are true:
  1. No non-color indicator (e.g., no underline, no icon)
  2. Color difference is the *only* cue for meaning
  3. Element is present in *current viewport at test time*
  4. No `aria-label` or fallback text

